06837nam a22009615i 9789048535446DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20192019ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485354467 a10.1515/97890485354462doi  a(DE-B1597)525769  a(OCoLC)1089625030  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aART0150002bisacsh04a382.09500aPicturing Commerce in and from the East Asian Maritime Circuits, 1550-1800 :bVisual and Material Culture, 1300-1700 /ced. by Tamara H. Bentley. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (364 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aVisual and Material Culture, 1300 –1700 ;v700tFrontmatter -- tTable of contents -- tList of plates and figures -- tAcknowledgements -- t1. People and things in motion: the view from the East -- tPart I. Circuits and exchanges -- t2. The maritime trading world of East Asia from the thirteenth to the seventeenth centuries -- t3. The junk trade and Hokkien merchant networks in maritime Asia, 1570–1760 -- t4. The trade activities of sixteenth-century Christian daimyo Ōtomo Sōrin -- tPart II. Commodities -- t5. From global to local: the diaspora of Asian decorative arts in colonial Latin America -- t6. Trans-Pacific connections: contraband mercury trade in the sixteenth to early eighteenth centuries -- t7. “The Features are Esteem’d very just”: Chinese unfired clay portrait figures of Westerners -- tPart III. Hybrid aesthetics -- t8. The global keyboard: music, visual forms, and maritime trade in the early modern era -- t9. Barbarian tropes framed anew: three Qing dynasty Chinese lacquer screens of Europeans hunting -- t10. Chinese porcelain, the East India Company, and British cultural identity, 1600–1800 -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCombining strikingly new scholarship by art historians, historians, and ethnomusicologists, this interdisciplinary volume illuminates trade ties within East Asia, and from East Asia outwards, in the years 1550 to 1800. While not encyclopedic, the selected topics greatly advance our sense of this trade picture. Throughout the book, multi-part trade structures are excavated; the presence of European powers within the Asian trade nexus features as part of this narrative. Visual goods are highlighted, including lacquerwares, musical instruments, Chinese bronze coins, unfired ceramic portrait figurines, and Chinese, Japanese, Korean, and Southeast Asian ceramic vessels. These essays underscore the significance of Asian industries producing multiples, and the rhetorical charge of these goods, shifting in meaning as they move. Building reverberations between merchant networks and the look of the objects themselves, this richly-illustrated book brings to light the Asian trade engine powering the early modern visual cultures of East and Southeast Asia, the American colonies, and Europe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aCultural Studies. 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aEast Asia and North East Asia. 4aEconomics and Finance. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aModern History. 7aART / History / General.2bisacsh  aMaritime Trade Early Modern Trade Early Modern Art East Asian Trade Networks Asian Export Art.1 aBentley, Tamara H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBentley, Tamara H., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChin, James K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevine, Victoria Lindsay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNishida, Hiroko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPierce, Donna, e